- cs.NA (Numerical Analysis): The paper discusses the discretization of the TDC-based formulation using isogeometric analysis and presents numerical results for benchmark tests, which involves numerical methods and analysis. 
- cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science): The paper applies the TDC-based formulation to shell geometries that are zero-isosurfaces, which is relevant to computational engineering and science. 
- cs.CG (Computational Geometry): The paper discusses the use of surface meshes and element-wise parametrizations in the discretization of the TDC-based formulation, which involves computational geometry concepts. 
- cs.ME (Mechanical Engineering): The paper presents a new formulation of the Kirchhoff-Love shell theory, which is relevant to mechanical engineering.
